dismissalComment.html: back of a length tailing past the hips down the leg side, goes across to flick and misses. Wide called down the leg side as the keeper fumbles. They take an easy single and Khushi turns to come back for two before there's a big mixup. Mendis gave chase to clean up his own mess but Kasun Rajitha gets to the ball first coming in from the deep fine leg rope and fires a one bounce throw to the relay to the fielder Charith Asalanka standing over the stumps. Bails are taken off with Khushi at least a foot short. Very clumsy from Khushi. Ayaan called for a second late and then changed his mind after two strides, but Khushi should never really have left his crease at all to begin the second run as it was never on.

commentTextItems.html: good length ball on sixth stump, shuffles across his stumps to scoop this over the keeper to the fine leg rope for the winning runs. Sri Lanka wallop Oman by 10 wickets reaching the target with 35 overs to spare.

commentPostTextItems.html: 12.48 pm Well, this match is over just a minute or two before Scotland has completed their first innings against the UAE on the other side of Bulawayo. That underscores how swift Sri Lanka have raced to victory here. Wanindu Hasaranga is on his way to being Player of the Tournament if he keeps up this bowling efficiency. Six wickets on match day one, and another five today. Karunaratne ices the chase with a half-century.

Wanindu Hasaranga unsurprisingly named Player of the Match for his 5 for 13: "This is a very good wicket to bowl for legspinners. I tried to bowl at the stumps. I think that's why I got wickets. I don't know what is the reason (why I keep taking wickets) but I try to bowl at the stumps and I do my normal basic things. The fast bowlers bowled really well and bowled good areas. Lahiru Kumara bowled really well and Kasun Rajitha supported him really well. These matches are really helpful for the World Cup tournament and are very helpful for us."

Oman captain Zeeshan Maqsood: "To play against Sri Lanka is proud for us. We have learned a lot from them, the way their bowlers bowled and their batters. First 10 overs, we lost too many wickets early on. We are tested now and that is good for us. Now we know what we need to do going forward. The positive for us is we have two wins. We cannot lose hope and we have to feel pride and play well. We have to forget this game and move forward. [Ayaan Khan's innings] He played very well. Unfortunately he couldn't get a 50 but hopefully he'll get more in the next games."

Sri Lanka captain Dasun Shanaka: "It's not about the toss. It's about the body language and the intent. Lahiru Kumara and Kasun Rajitha, they started really well and showed the intent. We don't take any team lightly. We need to bring our A game whatever the opposition is. Another six games to go so we are planning to give 100% when we come to the field. [On Hasaranga] He's a champion. Whenever I throw him the ball, he delivers for me. Very good to see him keep getting five-wicket hauls and man of the match awards. I think the future is really bright and they support staff and management has done a good job to keep the environment calm."

That's it for today's live coverage of this game. Scotland and UAE are currently in the innings break so by all means flip over to the commentary feed of that match to catch all of the UAE chase as they try to haul down Scotland's 282. On behalf of Madushka Balasuriya, I'm Peter Della Penna. Take care!

commentPostTextItems.html: Andrew Foruria: "As one sided as this game is, this shows that the Associates need to be given fixtures against the Full Members more regularly - they're never going to get to their level if they never get the chance play them." The other thing to remember is that Sri Lanka is truly an outlier among the Full Members. They have a historic reputation for smoking Associate teams because their bowlers in particular are so incredibly unique that Associate teams have no clue how to play them. It's only a few days since Oman beat Ireland after all chasing a total just short of 300.

dismissalComment.html: back of a length tailing past the hips down the leg side, goes across to flick and misses. Wide called down the leg side as the keeper fumbles. They take an easy single and Khushi turns to come back for two before there's a big mixup. Mendis gave chase to clean up his own mess but Kasun Rajitha gets to the ball first coming in from the deep fine leg rope and fires a one bounce throw to the relay to the fielder Charith Asalanka standing over the stumps. Bails are taken off with Khushi at least a foot short. Very clumsy from Khushi. Ayaan called for a second late and then changed his mind after two strides, but Khushi should never really have left his crease at all to begin the second run as it was never on.

The umpires give it out initially before deciding to ask for confirmation from the third umpire. Indeed he's taken this reaching in front of his right ankle, not remotely close to ever touching the ground.

In the event of teams finishing on equal points in their Group
a) The team with the greatest number of wins in its Group will be placed in the higher position.
b) If there are teams with equal points and equal wins in the Group stage, then in such case the team with the higher net run rate in the Group stage will be placed in the higher position
c) If two or more teams are still equal, they will be ordered according to the head to head match played between them (points then net run rate in those matches).
d) If the above does not resolve the Group ordering, or if all matches within a Group produce no results, then any tied teams will be ordered as per their original Group Stage seedings and the top 3 teams in each Group will progress to the Super Six stage.
In the event of teams finishing on equal points in the Super Six stage a) The team with the greatest number of wins in all of the matches throughout the competition against the other Super Six stage qualifiers will be placed in the higher position.
b) If there are teams with equal points and equal wins in the Super Six stage, then in such case the team with the higher net run rate in all matches played against the other Super Six qualifiers will be placed in the higher position
c) If two or more teams are still equal, they will be ordered according to the head-to-head match(es) played between them (points then net run rate in those matches).
d) If still equal, any teams that cannot be separated in this way shall be placed according to their original Group seeding.
e) If the above does not resolve the Super Six stage ordering, or if all matches within the Super Six stage produce no results, then the order of finishing will be determined by the team's performances in the Group stage as follows: Group standing, most points, most wins. If still equal, any teams that cannot be separated in this way shall be placed according to their original Group ranking.
